# Avoid Defensive Code

Write code that trusts invariants and contracts. Avoid redundant checks, excessive null guards, and "just in case" validation when the caller or design guarantees the condition.

## Examples

```csharp
// ❌ BAD - defensive null check when dependency is always injected
public void DoWork()
{
    if (_service == null) return;
    _service.Execute();
}

// ✅ GOOD - trust DI; if null, fail fast
public void DoWork()
{
    _service.Execute();
}
```

```csharp
// ❌ BAD - TryGetValue when key is guaranteed to exist
if (_dict.TryGetValue(key, out var value))
    Process(value);

// ✅ GOOD - direct access when invariant holds
var value = _dict[key];
Process(value);
```

```csharp
// ❌ BAD - redundant validation of internal state
private void OnButtonRemoved(string group, string buttonId)
{
    if (group != _view.Group) return;
    if (!_buttons.TryGetValue(buttonId, out var entry)) return;  // redundant if event contract guarantees it
    // ...
}

// ✅ GOOD - trust the event contract
private void OnButtonRemoved(string group, string buttonId)
{
    if (group != _view.Group) return;
    var entry = _buttons[buttonId];
    // ...
}
```

## When Defensive Code Is Appropriate

- Public API boundaries (validate external input)
- I/O or external system calls
- Explicitly documented preconditions that callers might violate

## Rationale

- Less noise, easier to read
- Fail fast surfaces bugs instead of hiding them
- Invariants enforced once (design, DI, contracts) instead of everywhere
